<TITLE> European shares down, autos lead; eyes on data, ECB </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 FRANKFURT, June 4 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European shares opened lower on Monday, retreating from six-and-a-half-year highs hit on Friday, with autos the leading sector decliners in early trade. The pan-European FTSEurofirst 300 index fell 0.14 percent to 1,623.61 points by 0713 GMT. DaimlerChrysler shares fell 1 percent. London's FTSE 100 index eased 0.2 percent, Frankfurt's DAX was down 0.3 percent and the French CAC 40 also dropped 0.3 percent. Later in the session, eyes will be on euro-zone April producer prices at 0900 GMT and US April factory orders at 1400 GMT. European Central Bank (ECB) President Jean-Claude Trichet speaks on "Policies that Sustain Prosperity and Promote Inclusion" at 0900 GMT, and investors will be on the lookout for interest rate clues in the run-up to the ECB monetary policy meeting on June 6. "A 25 basis point hike on Wednesday is universally expected by economists with clear upside risk for rates in the second half of the year," Dutch bank ING said in a note
